<paragraph blockId="35.[192,1441,1059,1244]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,744,1059,1083]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">Identification, taxonomy, and variation.</emphasis>
Both sexes are typically unsilvered, sympatrically occurring with silvered forms being those of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Scott et al. 1998)" baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[658,1128,1091,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atlantis" subSpecies="pahasapa">
<emphasis box="[658,909,1091,1115]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">S. atlantis pahasapa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, J. A. &amp; N. G. Kondla &amp; S. M. Spomer" box="[922,1119,1091,1115]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref45136" refString="Scott, J. A., N. G. Kondla, and S. M. Spomer. 1998. Speyeria hesperis and Speyeria atlantis are distinct species. Papilio 8: 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="1998">Scott et al. 1998</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Cliff Ferris (pers. comm.) notes that both ‘ 
<emphasis box="[386,530,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">S. h. lurana</emphasis>
’ and ‘ 
<emphasis box="[597,776,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">S. a. pahasapa</emphasis>
’ fly together and interbreed (or at least copulate) in the Big Horn Mountains, Washakie Co., 
<collectingRegion box="[632,752,1155,1179]" country="United States of America" name="Wyoming" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">Wyoming</collectingRegion>
. The status or distinctness of these two subspecies should be further evaluated. 
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, J. A." box="[462,625,1187,1211]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 129" refId="ref45004" refString="Scott, J. A. 2008 a. Corrections / reviews of 58 North American butterfly books. Papilio 19: 1 - 129." type="journal article" year="2008">Scott (2008a)</bibRefCitation>
suggests that these Big Horn populations best be called ‘ 
<emphasis box="[1334,1419,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">lurana</emphasis>
x 
<emphasis box="[192,283,1219,1243]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">dennisi</emphasis>
’. Adult wingspan is on average 
<quantity box="[668,754,1219,1243]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="35" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="55.0">55 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[192,1166,1283,1307]" box="[192,1166,1283,1307]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,288,1283,1307]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">Range.</emphasis>
Black Hills, 
<collectingRegion box="[442,615,1283,1307]" country="United States of America" name="South Dakota" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">South Dakota</collectingRegion>
. Also recorded in 
<collectingRegion box="[827,944,1283,1307]" country="United States of America" name="Wyoming" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">Wyoming</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Grey, L. P. &amp; A. H. Moeck &amp; W. H. Evans" box="[957,1153,1283,1307]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34" pagination="129 - 147" refId="ref39693" refString="Grey, L. P., A. H. Moeck, and W. H. Evans. 1963. Notes on overlapping subspecies. II. Segregation in the Speyeria atlantis of the Black Hills (Nymphalidae). Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 17: 129 - 147." type="journal article" year="1963">Grey et al. 1963</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[192,1440,1347,1403]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,357,1347,1371]" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">Life history.</emphasis>
I observed numerous individuals using creeks as flyways and feeding on various flowers in Spearfish Canyon, 
<collectingRegion box="[420,591,1379,1403]" country="United States of America" name="South Dakota" pageId="35" pageNumber="34">South Dakota</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
